               <p>THOMAS OSBORNE. I am a shoemaker, and lodge at the sign of the Victory, near Hackney-road. On the evening of the 13th of August I saw the prisoner go out of the skittle-ground into the field; I spoke to Massingham, and he went after him; I saw him take a ball from him, and he said he was very sorry.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-272-person1510">
                  JAMES 
                  MASSINGHAM
               <interp inst="t18280911-272-person1510" type="surname" value="MASSINGHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-272-person1510" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-272-person1510" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am servant to Mr. Skiven, who <rs id="t18280911-272-viclabel1398" type="occupation">keeps the <placeName id="t18280911-272-crimeloc1399">Victory public-house, in Cambridge-street, Hackney-road</placeName>
